"(1)  \nThe high, concrete arches of the High Line cast long, wavering shadows across the glowing grids of late afternoon. Zoe’s fingers trembled as she stepped onto the sun-baked platform, the air thick with the tang of roasted nuts and the low hum of servers. Around her, dozens of hunched silhouettes bent over terminals, their faces illuminated by neon blues and greens. Flickers of code scrolled in endless loops on screens, merging with the pulse of distant bass from the DJ setup. She could taste the electric anticipation as the final hour approached—every eye in the crowd fixed on the judges’ table, waiting for the moment someone would present their last stand. But her own heart was a drum in her chest. The demo wire had barely been plugged in when she noticed the first glitch: a pixel in the corner of her main interface stuttering, as if reality itself was buffering.\n\n(2)  \nNow, the time read June 14, 2025 on every digital clock above, its digital white light flickering in sync with the anxiety in the room. Zoe Brown stood rigid at the microphone, her project—a neural interface for real-time translation—hovering between finished and broken. The crowd was silent except for the low murmurs of $entity_1 and $entity_2, both nervously shuffling notes. As she prepared to click \"Run,\" the projection screen stuttered violently, then split into jagged lines. The code dissolved, replaced by a flicker of static that coalesced into the warped face of her own reflection, but twisted, eyes too wide, mouth opening in a silent scream. Her voice cracked mid-sentence, the room falling into a chilling, collective stillness. No one moved. Even the DJ’s music faltered, as if the world itself was holding its breath, waiting for her to remember what she should do—or what it would cost to proceed."